'''K<U+00E5>re Dorenfeldt T<U+00F8>nnesson''' (born 1 January 1926) is a Norwegian historian.

He was born in [[Ski, Norway|Ski]], and grew up in [[B<U+00E6>rum]].<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=K<U+00E5>re T<U+00F8>nnesson|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Knut|last=Kjeldstadli|authorlink=Knut Kjeldstadli|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://nbl.snl.no/K%C3%A5re_T%C3%B8nnesson|language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> He has resided at [[Ringstabekk]]<ref name=ntb>{{cite news|title=K<U+00E5>re T<U+00F8>nnesson 75 <U+00E5>r 1. januar|agency=Norwegian News Agency|date=13 December 2000|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and [[Hamang]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jubilanter|date=31 December 2010|work=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He is the father of [[Stein T<U+00F8>nnesson]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Stein T<U+00F8>nnesson|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|url=http://snl.no/Stein_T%C3%B8nnesson|language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref>

He [[examen artium|finished]] his seconary education at [[Valler Secondary School|Valler]] in 1944, and after enrolling in philological studies at the [[University of Oslo]] in 1945 he graduated with the [[cand.philol.]] degree in history in 1952. His master's thesis delved into [[causality]] in th writings of [[Alexis de Tocqueville]]. In 1959 T<U+00F8>nnesson took the [[dr.philos.]] degree with the thesis ''La d<U+00E9>faite des sans-culottes'', "The Defeat of the [[Sans-culottes]]".<ref name=nbl/><ref name=ntb/>

He was a lecturer in history at the University of Oslo from 1958, [[research fellow]] from 1960, [[docent]] from 1964 and professor from 1969 to 1991.<ref name=nbl/> From 1973 to 1975 he was the [[dean (academic)|dean]] at the Faculty of History and Philosophy.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=K<U+00E5>re T<U+00F8>nnesson|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|url=http://snl.no/K%C3%A5re_T%C3%B8nnesson|language=Norwegian|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> After retiring from the professorship, he he was a scholar in [[NAVF]] and the [[Research Council of Norway]]. Larger works include volume four of ''Sentraladministrasjonens historie'' in 1979 and  volume ten of ''[[Aschehougs verdenshistorie]]'' in 1985. This was also translated to Swedish and also reissued in 2001. In 1989 he marked the 200th anniversary of the [[French Revolution]] with the book ''Revolusjonen som rystet Europa''. This too was translated into Swedish.<ref name=nbl/> In 2007 he released a biography on [[Madame de Sta<U+00EB>l]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Frihetselsker og feminist|last=Bj<U+00F8>rnskau|first=Erik|date=11 August 2007|work=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

A [[Festschrift]] in T<U+00F8>nnesson's honor was released in 1995,<ref name=nbl/> and he is a fellow of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]].<ref name=ntb/>

